s mistake after a perfectly timed jump to the side of the swinging man had sent him hurtling into a trash heap on his own momentum. The drunkard had apparently not learned his lesson completely and had come around again, this time trying instead for a kick to Dharshan’s head. He had no time to stand and marvel at how the man was even athletic enough to get his foot up that high, instead he dropped down to the ground and kicked the drunk’s other leg out from under him. Dharshan had quickly rolled out of the way of the falling man, who fell face first into the dirt. By this time a small crowd of people had gathered around the spectacle, but it had all happened so fast that not much was seen other than the large man lying down in the street.<br>
              <br>
Word of the incident with the drunk had quickly spread around town and finally ended up landing Dharshan an interview with the city council about becoming a city patrolman. He never considered beating up a drunk to be a very difficult thing to do, but decided not to argue the point. Even considering that the position of a patrolman was one notch below the city guard in rank, it was still a very honoring proposal for Dharshan. <br>
              <br>
Though he had wanted to be accepted into the ranks of the city patrolmen, there was one small quirk that only someone such as himself would have been disappointed about, and that was the fact that all the guards, including the patrolmen, were required to wear a suit of iron armor, which in his opinion was rather large, heavy, and clumsy. Dharshan had been determined not to be required to wear the armor and had let the council know that he would not accept the job if he was forced to wear it against his will. The city council debated over the situation and a couple of days or so afterwards decided that, because of his small build, the armor’s weight would probably end up hampering his abilities before it would ever help him out in any way, therefore he would not be required to wear it. The following day he was sworn in as a new city patrolman.  <br>
              <br>
He had been a patrolman ever since and enjoyed the job very much, if indeed it could have even been called a job. The pay was not much, but the flexible hours and often dangerous and exciting encounters with the riff raff of the city were more than enough to make up for it. Plus, he had permission to use deadly force when he deemed it necessary. Which he often did without remorse.<br>
              <br>
For the time being Dharshan was on his way to the local pub, the “Moneysnatcher”. The pub had originally been named the “Dark Brew Tavern”, referring to its signature brew, a very potent, dark colored liquid that almost screamed out that it had come from the sewers. The sickening color couldn’t keep people away from it though, and the barkeep had tagged on a price that was just on the verge of price gouging, but not enough to keep people from buying one after the other. Therefore, the people always referred to the pub as the “Moneysnatcher”. This name being as popular as it was, the barkeep had decided that if the first name wasn’t even used by his visitors that he’d just call it what it should be called, hence the name “Moneysnatcher”.  <br>
              <br>
Dharshan had never bothered to buy the drink, and didn’t really care to buy it any time soon, preferring instead to keep his wits about him. Actually, all he ever did at the pub was to see if he could pick up any information on the latest events that had occurred around the town that particular day. Most of the people that frequented the pub were of the adventurous type and had just returned from their excursions outside of the city gates. Many of them chose to speak quite loudly, probably so that everyone would know of their latest adventures and all the great things they had done. Dharshan considered most of them to be your run of the mill blowhard, exaggerating much of what they said. Yet over the years he had gotten a good idea of who to believe and who not to. <br>
              <br>
Dharshan pushed open the two swinging doors and entered into the building. It was just starting to get dark out and most of the people had returned to the city for refuge over the night. One thing was different today though and immediately jumped out at Dharshan, the pub was not full of shouting drunks like usual. Instead they all looked rather glum and were all hunched over their drinks, not saying much of anything at all. Dharshan glanced around at the few people that were in the room, which had been another thing that appeared out of the ordinary, the building normally being so full that most of the occupants had no place to sit, being forced to stand most of time. Today there was at maximum only a third of the people that routinely packed the building. Dharshan identified one of his fellow dwarven patrolmen by the crossed sword and hammer symbol on the front, and probably the back, of his breastplate. The sword and hammer symbol was used on all patrolmen to help the commoners identify them, and was even sewn onto the vest that Dharshan was wearing. <br>
              <br>
The dwarf was sitting at one of the smaller tables in the room with his head bent over in his hands. A dwarf of slightly larger stature than was normal for his kind, yet small enough to not be able to sit comfortably at the bigger tables in the room. Dharshan walked over to him and with considerable strain on his legs sat down at the other end of the small circular table. Dharshan glanced around the room one more time before turning to face the dwarf. <br>
              <br>
“Hello there, the name’s Dharshan,” he extended his hand to the dwarf, but the little man appeared uninterested in the human’s attempts at conversation, not even raising his head to look at the person who had spoken to him. “I was wondering why this place looks so dead today, do you happen to know why?”, the dwarf still made no movement. Dharshan peered at the dwarf, wondering if he had maybe gone unconscious or had too much to drink and was experiencing the consequences. Then the Dwarf slowly lifted up his head and set his teary eyed gaze on Dharshan. <br>
              <br>
“Dead!?”, the dwarf let out sharply, all the while looking as if he was trying to hold back more tears, “Dead is exactly the right word for what is going on right now. I lost three of my best friends in a battle tonight, and after hearing of all the friends of the others here that were slain, I do not wish to be bothered right now. Please leave me be.”<br>
              <br>
Dharshan continued to sit at the table, stunned by what he had just heard the dwarf say. It was not uncommon to hear of some serious injuries and occasionally deaths in a day’s worth of adventuring, but never of such magnitude as had just been described to him. Suddenly it all started to come together. These people had probably all stumbled across some sort of tribe, probably goblins or orcs, or worse, trolls. The greatly feared Ogres were a possibility also, but many of them did not travel in packs in these areas. Also, much of the adventurers of the city traveled in separate small groups. Their scattered forces would have been no match for a fully assembled group of creatures bent on their destruction. Dharshan decided to try to pull a little more information out of the emotionally unstable dwarf. <br>
              <br>
“How did they die?”, Dharshan asked, trying not to sound too nosy. The dwarf squirmed in his chair and looked as if he was going to suddenly break down into a pool of even more tears, yet he quickly regained control of himself to some extent and looked straight into Dharshan’s eyes. <br>
              <br>
“Goblins,” the dwarf appeared to fill with anger as he mentioned the name, “the wretched things killed me friends and me friend’s friends, but I’ll get me revenge! Only a matter of time before they’re all punished fer’ their wickedness! Vile, wicked beasts! They’ll all die! I’ll kill ‘em all, I will!” the dwarf put his head back in his hands and continued to mumble about killing goblins, while Dharshan quietly slid out from under the tiny table and left the dwarf to himself. <br>
              <br>
“Goblins huh?”, Dharshan said to himself as he slowly made his way toward the doors of the building. He had heard quite enough for tonight, at least enough to keep him busy for a long while.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
              <br>
Dharshan entered into Mintrak’s Forge, the weapons shop he had come to grow so fond of. It was the only place that he knew of that sold the kind of weapon he liked; daggers, lots and lots of daggers. In fact, the store specialized in the making of daggers, not to mention throwing knives, and even a few short swords. Dharshan walked up to a display case which contained a few rather expensive looking gold daggers. A tall wiry barbarian, Mintrak himself, stood behind the case and watched. Dharshan guessed the blacksmith’s height to be very close to seven feet tall. <br>
              <br>
“What can I get for you today, Dharshan?”, the man held a long, shiny dagger that he had probably crafted himself and was wiping the blade down with a dirty towel. <br>
              <br>
“Well, I really need some more replacement throwing knives and probably a pair of daggers that are significantly better than these that I have.” Dharshan reached both his hands behind the vest that he wore and pulled the two aging daggers which he had already possessed out of their hidden sheathes. Dharshan turned the daggers around in his hands ‘til he held their blade side, a common courtesy among people who meant no harm to each other, and then proceeded to set them down on the display case. The man picked one of the daggers up and brought it close to his eyes. Examining it for a short while he then set the dagger back onto the case. <br>
              <br>
“Hmmmm… these aren’t all that bad really, just a little tarnished is all,” Mintrak exclaimed, “but I’ll see what I can find in the back to suit your needs.” The man disappeared into the darkly lit back room. <br>
              <br>
Dharshan had learned by now that most of the expensive daggers in the display cases were mostly just for looking at, nothing more than just decorations for some rich nobleman’s home. The blades were not very sharp at all and they probably would have broken in two if used on anything other than someone’s skin. The blades therefore were almost useless if they were to be used on most any armored creature, and a majority of people, if they were smart that is, always wore some sort of armor. Even Dharshan, who never really liked wearing the stuff, had a very lightweight, sleeveless ringmail tunic concealed underneath his vest.<br>
              <br>
“Significantly better you say?”, asked Mintrak from the back room. Dharshan could hear the clanking sounds of metal coming together. The barbarian was obviously looking for something in particular.<br>
              <br>
“Yes, if you can find anything,” replied Dharshan. The clanking sounds continued on for a moment, then the room went silent. A grave silence, to the point where only the wind outside the shop could be heard. Close by someone’s footsteps were also heard coming from outside, but soon passed on by and subsided. Dharshan expected to see Mintrak any second now, but he never appeared. The silence continued on, Dharshan almost to the point of going back and checking on the barbarian. Then Mintrak suddenly reappeared from the back room holding a couple of very dangerous looking daggers. Both weapons looked identical and like nothing he had seen before. They looked like any other normal dagger, except for the fact that positioned along the side of the tip of each dagger were a couple of long, bent back hooks, one on each side of the blade. The hooks were almost separate daggers in themselves and ran along the side of the middle dagger part, the blades each stopped at about three-fourths of the way down the middle part and left a gap of about an inch between themselves.    <br>
              <br>
“These are a very rare type of dagger,” the weapons sparkled in the candle lit room as the smith twisted them every which way, “they are called shantoobi and are a special design that was begun by my great grandfather, whom they are named after.” The smith handed the two weapons to Dharshan, “As you can see, they sort of work like a fish hook, very deadly indeed.” Dharshan stared wide eyed at the two weapons. He never knew that such a design had existed, but now he was asking himself why he had never thought of the idea before. “I made them myself,” the tall barbarian added, sounding rather proud of his work, “it was a long and hard decision for me to show these to you, as I’m sure you noticed.” <br>
              <br>
“Yes, I see now why it would take you so long to decide,” Dharshan smiled at the smith as he gave the daggers back. He then reached into the pouch that he wore around his waist. It contained most of his survival supplies, including money, food rations, bandages, and other survival related items. In fact, the only thing he did not have in his pouch were his daggers and throwing knives, which were all neatly concealed underneath his specially made vest. He pulled his hand back out, this time with a handful of gold coins which he set on the display case next to his own daggers. <br>
              <br>
The smith chuckled to himself, “Dharshan my friend, I know that I have given you great deals on my weapons before, but these are very special to me and I must at least make some sort of profit on my items,” Mintrak rubbed his chin with his finger as if some grand thought had suddenly appeared in his mind. Dharshan knew what Mintrak was thinking, and he knew what he was going to say next. It was no surprise when he was correct in his expectations. “Perhaps you have maybe a little more than this?”, Mintrak asked as he estimated the weight of the coins in his hand. Dharshan had already thrust his own hand back into the pouch before the smith had even started talking. Again he revealed a handful of gold coins and set them on the case along with the others. <br>
              <br>
“Aaaaaahhh…… now we are getting somewhere, these will most certainly provide the funds I need to make more shantoobi,” the smith then left the display case he was standing behind and made his way over to another one which contained a large selection of throwing knives, it being the only case with anything useful in it. All of them had been categorized by an animal’s name, and each knife went along with the name that it was associated with. Such as a serpent knife, which was small, sleek, and lightweight. Then there was the biggest joke in the shop, being the cumbersome, but cheap, sloth knife. Mintrak had earlier informed Dharshan that these were the results of failed attempts at forging by his younger students. “You say you also wanted throwing knives, how many?”. <br>
              <br>
Dharshan checked his remaining supply, of which there were only two left, “I’d like six of the tigers please”. Dharshan had become quite fond of the tiger design knives, they were very fierce looking, and just as deadly. The smith took the requested throwing knives out of the case and brought them back over to where Dharshan had dumped all of his coins. The smith plopped the knives onto the case along with the shantoobi. <br>
              <br>
“I will let you have these knives and these two daggers in exchange for the money and your two daggers, plus that.” The smith pointed to the diamond ring on Dharshan’s left hand, which was actually quite fake. Dharshan didn’t argue with the barbarian though, the smith had said he wanted the ring. Lucky for Dharshan, the smith didn’t enquire as to the authenticity of the ring, and possibly the smith didn’t even care, perhaps desiring to take advantage of some other fool who knew no better. Dharshan took the knives and daggers he had bought and put them into their respective sheathes under his vest. Saying goodbye to the smith as he walked out of the shop, he strolled down the street feeling quite happy with the deal he had struck.<br>
              <br>
Dharshan now headed toward the barracks that had been assigned to his particular unit. He would end up sleeping this night and probably most of the following day. For he had concluded that he would need to be prepared for the upcoming events that would probably unfold the following night, and that meant plenty of rest. <br>
