<a href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=7821>Equipment</a> </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/bthesafehouse.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=blikquikksilver>Blik Quikksilver</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(11/12/01 1:57:09 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Chapter 2</span><hr size=1>               Tonight Dharshan was determined to go scout out the area just outside of the city walls in search of the goblins he had heard about. He had tried to sleep during most of the day, but had found it rather uncomfortable to force himself to get rest. Instead he had occupied himself with some less strenuous activities, such as card games with fellow patrolmen or practicing different techniques with his new shantoobi. He knew that he couldn’t waste too much energy, he would most certainly need it tonight. <br>
              <br>
Munching on an apple as he went, Dharshan left his barracks and began to walk down the empty streets. The streets of the city were almost always barren at this time, but Dharshan knew of the rogues and other outcasts who lurked in the shadows, and he knew that right this instant there was a very good chance that they were eyeing his every move. Dharshan felt safe though. He knew that the veteran thieves and murderers would not desire to get into more than they could handle. Instead, they watched for less fortunate people, or those who were obviously not learned in the survival techniques that were nearly a must have in the potentially dangerous city. That did not stop him from keeping a close eye on his surroundings though, noting every shadow and every sound that was humanly discernible. <br>
              <br>
He headed toward the city gates, being careful not to look overly nervous while clutching the hilt of one of his shantoobi. The sun had set about a half an hour ago and some stars had begun to appear in the increasingly dark sky. It was the perfect time to locate the goblin horde since about this time many of them were probably starting their campfires and settling down for the cold night ahead. <br>
              <br>
Most of the shops had been locked up now, including the blacksmith shop he had been at the night before. The only places open were the pub and a select few that thrived on night time business. The only reason the pub stayed open at night was the twenty-four hour surveillance that was provided by the city guards. Dharshan passed the last shop on the street before he began to see the gates loom up in the darkness. Finishing his apple, he chucked it off into the weeds by the side of the road. Suddenly a hand came around from behind and covered his mouth, while a sharp object was pressed up against his back.<br>
              <br>
“Don’t ya’ be tryin’ nothin’ stupid now ya’ hear,” a raspy voice whispered into his ear, “I promise that I’ll kill ya’ in a heart beat if ya’ do”. The hand left Dharshan’s mouth and began to search around in his pockets. Finding nothing in them, the robber then found the pouch at Dharshan’s side, “Well, well, well… what have we here?”, the robber’s hand tore the pouch from Dharshan’s belt. He could hear the robber behind him as he began to try and get the knot on the pouch undone. The thief fiddled with the knot for about a minute or so with his free hand, obviously becoming impatient as he let out grunts of frustration. <br>
              <br>
Then the robber made the mistake Dharshan had been patiently waiting for. The same mistake that many veteran robbers had learned not to make simply by watching rookie fools like this make it. The robber let the dagger leave Dharshan’s back so he could cut the tight knot that was beginning to get on his nerves. Dharshan had kept his left hand underneath his jacket the whole time, gripping one of the shantoobi as he prepared himself mentally and physically for the maneuver he would undergo. As soon as he felt the pressure of the robber’s blade leave his back he made a quick jump forward, then just as quickly he turned his torso counter-clockwise and brought his shantoobi around with the movement. Dharshan could now see the thief’s head, which was peering into the newly opened pouch and searching for money. With his weapon still in motion from his quick turn he guided the dagger straight into the side of the man’s skull, causing a sharp cracking noise and a final look of surprise from the man. Dharshan held the man up at arm’s length and then quickly pulled the dagger out of the man’s skull. The thief’s eyes popped wide open as he dropped the pouch and his weapon to the street. His legs slowly buckled underneath him as he crumpled to the ground. Blood began to flow from the fresh wound as a puddle of the red liquid formed underneath the man. Dharshan slowly turned his head from one side to the other as he gave a threatening glare to the dark shadows that seemed to be moving about now, almost as if to challenge anybody else who dared come near. They didn’t.<br>
              <br>
“Well now look at what you’ve done,” Dharshan said to the now lifeless corpse, “you’ve bloodied up my new dagger!” Dharshan picked up his pouch from the ground and tied it back onto his waist, then proceeded to drag the limp body to the undertaker’s shop, the Dead Man’s Hand, which coincidentally was the last shop on the street before the gates were reached. The shadows appeared to slide away from Dharshan as he approached the shop. Dharshan left the body on the porch, then using his dagger he etched his signature into the wooden frame of the door to notify the owner of the shop who had left the body on his doorstep. It wasn’t the first time for Dharshan to take matters into his own hands, and it probably would not be the last either.<br>
              <br>
Dharshan stepped off of the building’s porch and started back toward the gate again. He had hoped that he wouldn’t have to be forced to kill another fellow human. Unfortunately though, many of the people that were out at this time of night obviously weren’t shopping for goods or taking leisurely strolls through the dark and menacing alleyways. A majority of the dwellers in the streets, excluding himself, looked to make a profit off of others. They considered it their job, having no desire to actually do real work for a living, instead turning to a life of crime to try and make ends meet. A sad way to go through with life, Dharshan thought, but he had hope for them though. He had seen a steep decline in the scum that littered the streets of the good city ever since he had been set to work the roadways as a patrolman. His presence did not sit good with the bandits and outlaws around the area though. Many of them had placed large bounties on his head. Dharshan knew though that it was simply their way of getting something done that they could not do themselves. They wouldn’t scare him away and they wouldn’t take him down without a fight, he would make sure of that.  <br>
              <br>
He now came upon the gates of the city. Two guards and one dressed in the armor of that of an officer, a blue tinted suit of plate armor, stood at the gate, each one eyeing him with suspicion as he approached. When they saw the crossed sword and hammer on his tunic they appeared to relax a little more though. Dharshan then noted that lying just to the side of the gate, next to the wall, was a pile of burnt bones which were still emanating a stream of smoke into the air. These were oddly shaped though. Definitely not human and definitely not that of any wild animal. These were goblin bones, the remains of those that dared come near the wall’s long line of defense.<br>
              <br>
“State your name and your business, patrolman,” the officer stated. Dharshan took note that he bore the emblem of the commanding officer on his shoulder, he was probably only inspecting the troops since most of the commanding officers did not become involved with simple guard duty. <br>
              <br>
“I am Dharshan, second lieutenant patrolman of the mighty city of Karnador!” Dharshan straightened up and lifted his hand to his forehead. Trying as hard as he could, he gave a salute to the commanding officer, a sad salute, but a salute no less. He had never really taken the time to work on his saluting, considering it to be a waste of time, for he had never heard of any warrior who had won battles with his excellent salutes. “I am on a mission to scout out the territories of our enemies, the goblins,” the officer frowned slightly, either at the mention of the creatures or at Dharshan’s poor saluting capabilities. “They are responsible for the murdering of many people of the city and I intend to find out what they are up to.” <br>
              <br>
The officer inquisitively lifted up an eyebrow at Dharshan, “you, and you alone?”. Dharshan nodded his head in answer to the officer’s question. He had considered the fact that he would be alone on the mission and understood the consequences he would face if he was found, but he desired the stealth that would be achieved with a one man team. <br>
              <br>
“Yes, I will be the only one going,” Dharshan declared as he squared his shoulders, trying to possibly prove to the officer that he was capable. He knew that the commander would not look at his physique though. Every respectable person who was involved in military in one way or another that Dharshan had talked to, had told him that you can always tell a person’s determination through their eyes. Apparently, Dharshan’s eyes had been rather convincing to this particular officer that he was confident of his ability to stay alive. <br>
              <br>
The officer motioned for a guard to open up the gate. Dharshan watched as the large iron gate was slowly lifted up to reveal the path that led through the forest behind it. No guards stood outside the gate, yet there were two rather tall watchtowers on either side of the gate, each one containing an observer. Archers were also positioned along the wall to aid in the observation, but their main task was to fire upon anyone with bad intentions who dared to approach the fortified city. <br>
              <br>
Dharshan peered down the road that winded into the forest. He took pride in the fact that his continuous thriving in darkness had blessed him with an unusual ability to see in the night. Though not as honed as the dwarve’s or the elve’s sight, it was still considerably better than normal. This ability let Dharshan know immediately of the bodies that randomly lay about, the bodies consisted of dwarves, elves, humans, barbarians, and goblins, and all of them lay either directly on the road or just to the side of the road in the tall grass. He looked on in horror, suspecting that the adventurers had run for their lives from the goblins, but a majority of them hadn’t made it from what he could see. He suspected the goblins to still be nearby since there had obviously been no attempt at the retrieval of the fallen warriors.<br>
              <br>
He walked down the road a little ways as he heard the gate behind him creaking shut. He would have to deviate from the path though, because if there was anything he had learned about being stealthy it was that you never take the most obvious route when traveling, and the most obvious route was almost always the most traveled. He had heard stories of what had happened to lone travelers along the road and he did not desire to become one of those stories.<br>
              <br>
A thick fog hung over the swampy ground of the forested area on the left side of the path. The murky ground would make travel very awkward, but awkward travel was needed, for it would be least expected that he come through that area. The fog blanketed the whole section of trees and continued on to an unseen end somewhere in the depths of the forest. It would make his vision even more limited than it already was, but it would also help to mask his approach from any observers. He veered off to left and entered into the foggy forest. <br>
              <br>
As he slowly and soundlessly crept through the tall weeds that preceded the swampy areas, he began to etch marks into the trees so that he would be able to find his way home a little easier if he became disoriented. The plants slowly gave way to a dark and ominous swamp. It proved rather difficult to wade through, even though the muck barely rose above his knees. The stench of many different things that Dharshan didn’t want to know about began to waft up and meet him. Fortunately it was springtime, and the temperature reminded him of that fact. The various types of bloodsucking bugs that were buzzing around him were not all that pleasant though, for they thrived in this type of environment and occasionally landed on him to get their day’s meal or, as he figured, just to tick him off.<br>
              <br>
The smell of a cooking meal began to overtake the stench of the swamp and find its way to Dharshan as he continued to slog through the murky, wet ground. The smell confirmed his suspicions that the goblins were not far away as he attempted to change his course and follow the smell. As he neared the smell he tried to make his approach more silent, lifting his legs over the water and setting them down instead of pushing his legs through the muck. It was possible though, that the smell may have been the making of someone or something else other than the goblins, but Dharshan was not going to take any chances. <br>
              <br>
A light, probably the fire that cooked the meal he smelled, started to become visible in the distance. The swamp slowly became shallower, to the point where Dharshan could dart from tree to tree, quickly but quietly making his way closer to the light. Three large silhouettes of some kind of creature soon began to take shape. Dharshan crept closer until he could correctly identify them. <br>
              <br>
The sight almost made him puke. Three trolls were gathered around a campfire, the larger of the three was standing before the fire holding a large butcher’s knife and the other two sat on a fallen log with their backs to Dharshan while looking on in anticipation for the upcoming feast that they were slowly cooking over the fire. What was over the fire was the most horrific sight Dharshan had seen in quite a few years. A headless dwarf had been impaled with a large stick and was slowly roasting over the hot flames. This was the wonderful smell that had overcome him!? Dharshan attempted to calm himself a bit and looked slightly away as he listened to the trolls’ ongoing conversation.<br>
              <br>
“Me sayed ‘dat me wanted ‘da heart!”, said one of the trolls sitting on the log. He turned and gave the other troll a heavy punch in the arm. The punch probably would have broken the arm of any human but did not seem to faze the troll in the least. <br>
              <br>
“Wibmuk sayed ‘dat he want first!”, the other exclaimed as he returned the favor. The two began exchanging blows as they fell to the ground, each punch being a little harder than the last. <br>
              <br>
“you’s cut ‘dat out or not get nuttin’!”, the larger troll declared as he strolled over and kicked the two fighting trolls, “We not go ‘dis far ouda’ ‘da way just ta’ get us all bashed up over smelly liddle dwarfs, we need stay good an’ strong ta’ fights da’ udders wid’!” Both trolls glared at each other as they stopped punching and slowly got off of the ground and back onto their log. <br>
              <br>
“Why does I stick wid’ you guys when Mimbam easily find own dwarfs?” the other troll on the log asked. <br>
              <br>
“Cause you aint got ‘da brains ta’ know how ta’ cook ‘em right!” said Wibmuk to his accomplice.<br>
              <br>
Dharshan’s anger was too much for him to bear. He stepped out of the clearing and hurled one of his throwing knives straight into the back of the troll named Wibmuk. The troll jumped slightly at the feeling and toppled over the back of the log, landing on his back and driving the knife even farther into himself. Dharshan then unsheathed one of his shantoobi and sprinted up behind the other still sitting troll. Dharshan slit the troll’s throat before it even had time to look at its dead friend. Blood gushed out of the wound as the troll made a futile attempt to stop its quick flow. All to no avail, as he also toppled to the ground. The other troll had witnessed both attacks and now seethed with anger.<br>
              <br>
“Dumb human! You no kill da’ trolls! Now me cut head off to burn in fire!”. Bringing his cleaver up above his head, the troll charged at Dharshan. Dharshan anticipated the assault and dodged to the side as the troll ran past and slashed his cleaver through a tree that had stood behind where Dharshan was previously standing. Turning around to face the troll, Dharshan was overjoyed to see that it still had its back turned to him. A quick stab into the back of the troll’s leg only angered it more. This time it spun the cleaver around in a wide arc, connecting with nothing once again as Dharshan jumped back and avoided the dangerous weapon, but in the process he slammed into a tree behind him. The contact with the tree caught him completely off guard, knocking the wind out of him and causing a sharp pain in his back. Dharshan fell to the ground and lay unmoving. In the meantime, the tree that the troll had sliced through had fallen on top of the troll’s own head, which should have killed the thing, but the troll simply brushed it off. <br>
              <br>
The troll lazily walked over to Dharshan, overconfident that the fight was pretty much over and that the human could do nothing more to harm him. The troll rose the cleaver above his head once again, but winced in pain as he felt something pass through his kneecap. He let the cleaver drop behind him and grabbed for the shantoobi sticking out of his leg, hopping up and down on one foot until Dharshan took his other shantoobi out of its sheath and destroyed the troll’s other good kneecap, making him crumple to the ground with a scream of agony.<br>
              <br>
Dharshan struggled to sit up, searching for air as he watched the troll screaming and thrashing about on the ground. The troll wouldn’t be going anywhere soon, but Dharshan knew that they healed very quickly and was determined to put him out of his misery. As he began to take precious oxygen into his lungs once again he crawled over to the troll and pulled one of the shantoobi out of its legs. Feeling no remorse for the dwarf killing troll, he drove the weapon directly into its brain. The troll no longer moved and all was quiet again.<br>
              <br>
Dharshan took comfort in the fact that he had once again looked death in the eyes and lived to tell about it. He rolled onto his back and took a much deserved rest, listening to the distinct sound of breaking twigs, the crackle of the fire, and … breaking twigs? Dharshan propped himself up onto his elbows and looked around as he listened closer for the sound he thought that he had heard. It had indeed been the sound of breaking twigs and there was definitely something lurking through the fog toward him. <br>
              <br>
Dharshan could now see what he had heard, and it was not encouraging. Dark shadows turned to sickly colored skin, which in turn formed into a group of scowling goblins. Dharshan reached over to the dead troll next to him and pulled both of his shantoobi out, then stood up to meet the oncoming goblins, six of which he had counted in all, but didn’t know of the one which had crept up behind him until it was way too late. Dharshan felt the hammering of a blunt object on the back of his head and dropped to the all too familiar ground.<br>
              <br>
Dharshan laid in wait for the killing blow to come, but it never did. Instead the goblin kicked him in the side, turning him over onto his back. Dharshan looked up, and through slightly blurred vision he saw what he believed to be an evil grin on the goblin’s face. Then he noticed in his dazed state of mind that it wasn’t a goblin at all. The troll that he had slit the neck of was already back up from the ground, his neck was healed and back to normal, and he now stood over him with a club in his hand. Dharshan now wished he had just taken the thing’s whole head right off, but it was too late now. Feeling himself slip into unconsciousness, he closed his eyes to the troll that would take his life. <br>
              <br>
For some reason though, he decided to open them again for what he believed to be the last thing he would ever see. He thought he saw a goblin standing over him now, along with the troll. As his vision continued to blur even more, he saw that they appeared to be glaring at each other, instead of him, probably arguing over who would kill the insignificant human. Dharshan noted in that small span of time that the goblin appeared to tower over the troll that had originally hit him. He had always thought that goblins were smaller than trolls, but figured that his mind was just playing games with him now. Nonetheless, the goblin would probably end up winning the argument if it was actually as big as Dharshan thought it was. He closed his eyes for the last time and let his mind slip away. If he was killed he wouldn’t want to feel it.<br>
