s a good sign for him, since the animals hardly ever came out when predators, such as trolls and goblins, were about. He struggled to open his eyes as he attempted to adjust to what seemed like a very bright light, hopefully the sun, shining directly in his face. Squinting his eyes he saw that the light was indeed the sun, indicating to him that he had been out for a while. It barely peeked in through the dense forest around him, but the clearing that he was positioned in the middle of had left a small gap in the treetops. Just enough for some rays of sun to make their way to him. He attempted to move his arms and legs around to see if anyone had tied him to anything, they moved as freely as ever before. <br>
              <br>
Dharshan lay in the soft ground, pondering for a moment how he could have possibly survived the night before. Maybe this was a dream? Perhaps he was actually being held captive by the goblins, and merely longed in his dreams to be in the swamp once again. There was no possible way that he could have escaped. And if he had, he didn’t remember any of it.<br>
              <br>
Dharshan lifted his hand up and gave himself a swift slap in the face… and it hurt… a lot. “Ouch!”, Dharshan yelped as he realized he had maybe put too much effort into it. He definitely wasn’t dreaming, and this was certainly the same spot where he had been knocked out the night before. How he could have ever escaped from the goblins was beyond his knowledge. Perhaps he had not even done it himself. Maybe some kind soul had come upon him and slain every creature there. Dharshan yearned for answers.<br>
              <br>
“You know, that’s not too good for you,” said a very deep voice from behind him. Dharshan sat up and turned to look at the person who had spoken to him. Then he stood up and grabbed for his weapons quicker than he had ever done so in his entire life. A massive goblin, probably close to eight feet tall, now stood before him, grinning and staring at him with his only eye. His right eye was covered with a black eye patch, but it could not cover the deep scar that came out on each side of the patch. He was also shirtless, which revealed an array of scars on his muscled chest. This confirmed what he had thought he saw the night before, but now that he saw the creature even more clearly, he now wished more than ever that he had been killed the night before. <br>
              <br>
“My weapons!”, Dharshan yelled out, searching in vain for his only way out of this mess. His vest had been removed and therefore he had no weapons to defend against this monstrosity. They were all gone, even his pouch had been taken. All of his hopes were dashed that very instant, but he was determined not to go down without a fight.<br>
              <br>
Dashing up to the goblin and jumping at the last moment he planted a kick directly into the large goblin’s chest, but bounced off and landed on the squishy ground, slightly knocking the wind out of himself. The goblin took a small step backward to keep his balance, but appeared unhurt as he continued standing his ground and watching the human with his one good eye. The big grin was still on his face. <br>
              <br>
“That’s not too good either,” he said, as the smile grew wider, “Methinks that maybe you’re not so smart, hurt yerself twice now you did.” The goblin bent down and offered a hand to Dharshan. <br>
              <br>
What is wrong with this goblin?! Dharshan thought to himself, why didn’t he fight!? Dharshan stood up on his own and lunged at the goblin with his fist, but the goblin caught his hand in mid-flight and held it there. Dharshan struggled for a short while, trying to release his hand from the iron grip of the goblin. It was no use though, the hold of the goblin was unbreakable. Setting his feet wide apart, Dharshan sent another powerful blow toward the goblin’s groin with his free hand. The goblin also caught this attempt by the human, now holding both of his hands in a mighty grip.  <br>
              <br>
“Let me go you foul beast!”, Dharshan spat at the goblin as his hands began to turn rather pale from the awesome pressure that the goblin was able to apply. The goblin kept his hands tightly gripped around Dharshan’s fists as the pain became nearly unbearable. Dharshan knew he was in trouble when he couldn’t even feel the pain any more, or his hands for that matter. He began to wonder if they were even hands any more. He expected blood to come out of the sides of the goblin’s grip sometime soon, as if the goblin had been simply squeezing a couple of grapefruits.  <br>
              <br>
“Very well,” stated the goblin as he finally obliged to the feeble human’s request, releasing the human and sending him reeling back to the ground on his own momentum. Dharshan lay in the spot where he dropped, replaying over and over in his mind what had just occurred. He looked down at his hands. They were still there, and they looked normal, but they hung limp since he could not feel them or move them in any way. The goblin now had his arms crossed over his wide chest and continued to stare at the little man. He appeared to be quite entertained by the person lying in front of him in the muddy ground. <br>
              <br>
Of all the goblins Dharshan had ever met in his lifetime, this one was the most unique. In its size, it loomed over all other goblins he had ever seen in his lifetime. In its vocabulary, it was even more fluent in the common language than some fellow humans Dharshan had met. Yet, the most interesting aspect was its personality. All goblins, in Dharshan’s mind, were the epitome of evil. They desired nothing more than to slaughter and eat everything and anything that got in their way. They did not know good or evil, they only knew and thought about murdering other beings and keeping themselves alive. They were mindless killing machines, desiring only to make life miserable for everyone around them, and they definitely could have cared less if someone was a respectable person. <br>
              <br>
Looking up at the immense bulk of the goblin, he began to view the creature in a different light than he had before. This goblin had no weapons of any kind except for his fists, which Dharshan had learned they could probably do some pretty gruesome things in and of themselves. He probably had Dharshan’s weapons hidden somewhere for his own safety though. He also did not have an evil scowl across his face, which was the norm for every other goblin Dharshan had ever known of. Instead, he had a big friendly smile on his face, but it still couldn’t cover up the goblin’s ugly facial features.<br>
              <br>
“Feeling better now?”, asked the goblin when he realized that the human wasn’t struggling for his life any more. Dharshan looked down at his hands and saw that they were gradually beginning to regain their color. Then the slow impending pain of what felt like pins and needles began to wash over them. Dharshan looked back up at the goblin; who, strangely enough, had a look of concern on his face. Dharshan decided to cut straight to the point.<br>
              <br>
“Why didn’t you kill me?”, he abruptly asked the goblin as he rubbed his hands together, hoping to ease their pain, “What do you intend to do with me now? Torture me for your amusement?” <br>
              <br>
“I’m not like that,” stated the goblin bluntly, as he once again offered to lift Dharshan off of the ground, “only kill when needed.” Dharshan did not accept the invitation of the goblin, but was becoming more comfortable around this strangely different character. “And you are one to understand meself’s motives,” added the goblin as he kept his hand outstretched for the human, “more so than my kin, that is for sure. Though I still think you’re not too smart.”<br>
              <br>
Dharshan ignored the hand of the goblin again and instead considered everything the goblin had said. It was apparent that the goblin meant him no harm, at the moment at least. Yet, Dharshan wondered if there were any other hidden motives behind the goblin’s friendliness. That is until he had a closer look at his surroundings.<br>
              <br>
The bodies of other dead goblins were strewn about in every direction. One of the bodies even hung limp over the high limb of a tree. Many of the carcasses were also missing their arms, while some even had no head. Strangely enough, they did not look like they had been cut off, the severed areas were way too rough for that. Dharshan shuddered at the thought of having his own arms or head torn off. Then he noticed that the dead bodies of the trolls had been thrown into the remains of the fire that they had been using themselves the night before, ending their terrorous lives forevermore. For it was universally known that trolls could not heal themselves when they were burnt to a crisp.<br>
              <br>
“Who did this?”, Dharshan asked as he indicated the dead bodies all around him, though he somehow figured that he already knew the answer to that. The goblin looked around himself and then turned back with a look of pride on his scarred face.<br>
              <br>
“As I said before, they do not understand my motives. They attacked 'til every last one of them’s blood stained the ground. Had it coming, yes they did,” the goblin said matter-of-factly as he strolled over to the armless and headless goblin hanging from the tree. The massive goblin walked as if he hadn’t a care in the world, he probably feared no one. And rightly so. “This one,” he said as he pointed at the dangling goblin, taking a small pause to admire his work, “very feisty he was.” <br>
              <br>
Dharshan now stood up and watched the large goblin as he lumbered around in the midst of the corpses. He made no move to run from the goblin, who now had his back turned to him, considering that the goblin could have probably run him down and slaughtered him in short order. In fact, he was rather intrigued by the huge creature and did not intend to leave. Instead, he wished to learn more of what kept this goblin in such good spirits, and what kept the beast from killing him. <br>
              <br>
The goblin paused at every body, it seemed that he was either looking for something or simply liked to admire his handiwork. Probably both, Dharshan ultimately decided.<br>
              <br>
“Methinks I have found it,” declared the goblin as he reached down toward a body at his feet. It was another goblin of slightly larger stature than was normal, but not as large as the one that stood over it. Dharshan suspected that the goblin had found his weapon. What he brought up in his hand didn’t seem all that impressive though. A simple, dark colored bead necklace, nothing fancy from what he could see. The goblin examined the necklace for a moment then turned back to Dharshan. “Yes, this is it,” the goblin confirmed, more to himself than anyone around him. The goblin wrapped the necklace around his huge neck and then slowly wandered back to where Dharshan stood.<br>
              <br>
“How ‘bout a real handshake now?”, the goblin thrust his big green hand toward Dharshan. Dharshan stood and stared blankly at the hand before him, but even surprised himself when after a short pause he reached out and firmly gripped the goblin’s hand. The goblin beamed a huge smile at Dharshan as he quickly pumped his hand up and down.<br>
              <br>
“Good, very good!”, shouted the goblin as he let go of Dharshan’s hand. “My name’s Kilmituk,” the goblin declared as he motioned for Dharshan to follow him, “and what might yer name be?”.<br>
              <br>
“I am Dharshan, second lieutenant patrolman of the city of Karnador,” he replied as he followed Kilmituk through the mushy ground. Kilmituk looked back at Dharshan with a befuddled look on his face.<br>
              <br>
“You? A patrolman?”, Kilmituk looked Dharshan up and down. “Naw, yer no patrolman,” said the goblin as he chuckled to himself, “too small, I’d break you in half.” Dharshan felt the hints of a smile coming onto his face, but quickly hid his amusement. He was not used to being around a creature that he normally would have slain in a second’s notice, and he didn’t really want to appear too comfortable in front of the humongous goblin.<br>
              <br>
Kilmituk finally stopped and reached his humongous arm deep into a small tree stump. Dharshan expected the goblin’s arm to get stuck, but the stump was just big enough for him to fit it in. <br>
              <br>
“These,” Kilmituk said as he began to bring his hand back out of the stump, “I think, are yours.” Indeed, this Kilmituk fellow was definitely not a normal goblin. He now held every last one of Dharshan’s weapons in his huge hand, including the pouch and his vest, and now he wished to give them back to him. Dharshan had been surprised many times in his life, but nothing prepared him for this. His jaw dropped as he accepted the weapons and the pouch.<br>
              <br>
Of all the people in the world, a goblin had been the one to save his life when he was destined to be a dead man. Even going so far as to stick around and keep the area safe from intruders. Dharshan could no longer hold his emotions in. Dropping to his knees in front of the goblin and bowing his head in humility, he put himself in the most vulnerable position possible before a goblin that could have taken him out of the world in the blink of an eye if he so desired. Not known to Dharshan though, the goblin had also been moved by the events unfolding before him.<br>
              <br>
“Surely, there is no other creature on this whole earth that is an equal to you in the mercy that you have shown to me today,” cried Dharshan as he kept his head bowed. “You have saved me from unspeakable torments by the hands of those evil creatures, and I cannot ever repay you. I am indebted to you. My life is yours and I will do whatever you bid me to do.” Dharshan did not struggle with the words in any way, for he truly meant what he had said. He had known the goblin for only a little while now, and already he had the utmost respect for him. Then he felt the touch of the goblin on the back of his head.<br>
              <br>
“You owe me nothing,” the goblin said as he brought Dharshan’s eyes up to meet his own, “you have already repaid me by accepting me for who I am. Never had I thought that yer kin could be so understanding of meself,” the goblin said as he lifted Dharshan back to his feet, “but I have been proven wrong.” Dharshan believed he saw a dying flame deep in Kilmituk’s sole eye. A flame possibly representing the last tiny remnant of what the goblin had once been before. He truly desired to know more about Kilmituk now.<br>
              <br>
“Why are you the way you are?” Dharshan asked as he believed he saw the flame in the eye of the goblin finally flicker and die out completely, “I mean, why aren’t you like the others of your kind?”               <br>
              <br>
The goblin pondered the thought as he stared into the tops of the trees. His form showed the scars of many battles. Although now unknown to Dharshan, there was far more behind them than simple fights. The goblin slowly lowered himself to the ground and sat facing the stump. <br>
              <br>
“Please sit down, I have much to explain to you.”<br>
