              <br>
He appeared to be dreaming, smiling happily as he rocked back and forth, and mumbling some gibberish that Dharshan could not understand while making strange gestures with his hands. Dharshan watched and wondered, not really knowing the significance of it all, but not willing to wake the happy goblin. Before Kilmituk had drifted to sleep he had instructed Dharshan to sit and wait. So that’s what he was going to do. <br>
              <br>
Dharshan looked down at his feet, beginning to grow tired of the goblin’s antics. Kilmituk had been asleep for over an hour now and the strange language he spoke was beginning to grow tiresome, considering that he could not even understand a word of it. All of it seemed pointless, but it was kind of funny that the goblin had a knack for talking in his sleep, if indeed it was sleep. When he looked back up though, the scene had changed drastically. Kilmituk now appeared to be extremely frightened. His whole body flailed about, his face showing a look of deathly fear. Dharshan considered intervening and waking up the frightened goblin, but heeded Kilmituk’s instructions and continued to watch the spectacle unfold before him. Kilmituk looked like he was trying to run from something, his mouth opened wide in terror. Yet, no screams or sounds of any kind came out. <br>
              <br>
Now the goblin stopped, the look of fear erased from his face. He sat on the ground, unmoving as he once again began to utter more phrases that Dharshan could not understand. This time he didn’t look happy though. His face was contorted in rage and the veins in his neck were popping out. The words he spoke were also coming out in a sharper tone of voice. Then his eye opened, and Dharshan believed he saw the flame in it as he had seen earlier. Fearing for his life, he sought to run, but was frozen with terror and not able to move at all. Then Kilmituk yelled something that nearly threw Dharshan off his stump. <br>
              <br>
“Ok mok degon quif!” <br>
              <br>
Kilmituk once again began flailing his arms about, a layer of sweat forming over his dark skin. It seemed this time though that he had a degree of control to his arm, almost as if he was attempting to strike something that was not there. The blows were powerful enough to coax Dharshan off of his stump as he moved away from the blindly swinging goblin. Kilmituk stopped abruptly and reached to the ground, picking up an object Dharshan couldn’t see. Bringing it up he appeared to put the unknown object around his neck. <br>
              <br>
Suddenly the goblin awoke from the dream as he looked around himself, being fully aware of his surroundings. Dharshan saw that the flame was gone from his eye now. It was apparent that the dream had taken a lot out of the tough goblin, his face was covered with sweat and he seemed to be having trouble sitting up. The goblin spotted Dharshan and saw that he was still there, then closed his eye again and fell backward, exhausted.<br>
              <br>
Dharshan stared at the tired goblin, stunned by his strange actions. He was beginning to question his original belief that the goblin was only dreaming, but he knew he would be learning the facts soon enough. He noticed that the sun had once again dipped below the horizon. The fog would soon be rolling in once again. He did not wish to stay in the forest for another night, but actually felt quite safe with the large goblin he had befriended lying on the ground in front of him. He would certainly prove a worthy ally if anything dared approach the clearing that they were in.<br>
              <br>
Kilmituk began to stir once again, opening his eye and glancing around.<br>
              <br>
“How long was I asleep?”, the goblin asked without raising himself from the ground.<br>
              <br>
“Well, actually only a few seconds, maybe a minute,” Dharshan replied, becoming more comfortable now that the goblin was awake once again.<br>
              <br>
“No, how long was I dreaming?”, the goblin still made no move to get up.<br>
              <br>
“Um… I’d say about an hour or so,” Dharshan found his way back to the stump and sat down again.<br>
              <br>
“Only an hour?”, the goblin hoisted himself into a sitting position, a confused look on his face, “then why do I feel so tired? What did I do while I was asleep?”<br>
              <br>
“Well, you were talking in a strange language most of the time. You appeared to be happy. Then you looked scared, and seemed as if you were fleeing from something. After a little while you stopped running, since that is what I assume you were doing. You became angry and started spitting out some really strange phrases, proceeding to yell something that I could not discern the meaning of. Then you started swinging at somethi-”.<br>
              <br>
“What did I yell?”, Kilmituk suddenly asked.<br>
              <br>
“Let’s see… I believe it went something like, ‘Ok mog tegon drif’, but I am no-”.<br>
              <br>
“Ok mok degon quif?”, Kilmituk interrupted again. <br>
              <br>
“Yes, that’s what it was,” said Dharshan.<br>
              <br>
The goblin brought himself back to his feet and paced back and forth on the ground, his hands clasped behind his back. He then turned to face Dharshan. <br>
              <br>
“You are sure this is what I said?”, inquired the goblin.<br>
              <br>
“I am positive,” replied Dharshan, confused about why it was so important to the goblin. The goblin looked into the treetops and closed his eye.<br>
              <br>
“It is as I suspected then,” Kilmituk said reluctantly to no one in particular. Turning his gaze back on Dharshan, he wandered back to the stump and sat back down in front of Dharshan. <br>
              <br>
“As I said before, there is much that must be explained,” Kilmituk opened his mouth wide and yawned, “afterward I must rest again.” The goblin reached up and felt the beads around his neck then dropped his hand back to his side. Drawing a deep breath, he began his story.<br>
              <br>
“My tale begins when I was a young child. Very early in my life I had been taken captive from my tribe, the Loose Tooth Clan which resided in the Garga Valley, in a raid by a neighboring clan of warrior goblins from the mountains, their tribe was known as the Broken Fist. My parents and most of my brethren were slaughtered in the raid, while I was spared. I became a slave to Grimbulkin, the heir to the throne of the Broken Fist. Grimbulkin was one of the most evil goblins I have ever known in my life, I was treated cruelly and often tortured for his amusement. I took it all in stride though, never showing my true emotions. Having few freedoms, I was often forced to work for the majority of the day and into the night, which allowed me very little sleep. I hardly ever got any breaks in that span of time. If I did stop working, I was often whipped or tortured.” <br>
              <br>
“Very rarely was I allowed any free time outside of my master’s hut. When I was allowed free time, I almost never left the hut, for fear of my life. Being a physically impaired goblin, I was unusually small and my spine was twisted from birth. I had no way of defending myself and was often beaten up by other goblins my age.”<br>
              <br>
“As I grew, I was granted more freedoms. The hours of working like a slave became fewer, and the whippings became less often. My master came to admire my stubbornness, nicknaming me ‘Stoneface’ because of all the punishment I was able to endure without breaking down. After a few more years he finally stopped me from household labor altogether, appointing me as his shieldbearer. As his shieldbearer I was given the privilege of riding into battle alongside the best warriors of the tribe. I was watched closely at first, but they became more and more sure of my loyalty, thinking that I had accepted them as friends.”<br>
              <br>
“I had not. In my heart I knew that I hated them, especially my master Grimbulkin. I often tried to think of ways to escape from, or even kill, the evil goblin. Yet I never had the guts to go through with my plans. All of the goblins’ evil desires had left a burning sensation in me, a sense that there was a better way of life than the murdering of innocent people. I often thought of what else was out in the world, what I could accomplish if I could escape from the tribe. My chance would soon come.”<br>
              <br>
“One day Grimbulkin decided set out for a hunting trip with a couple of his comrades, and I was to be his shieldbearer that day. It was the first time that I would be out of the camp for more than a day. I kept my loyalty ploy going and continued to happily obey any order that I was given. The day soon grew old and after a while the tired goblins appointed me to watch the camp as they rested.” <br>
              <br>
“A foolish mistake. I set out in the darkness, taking a spare sword with me. I ran for my life, for I knew that if I was found I would have many unspeakable things awaiting me back at the camp. I was not sure of where I was or what lay before me, but I only wished to put as much distance between meself and my master. Luck was with me that night, for I did not run into any predators of any kind, but as the sun rose into the sky I knew that by now I was probably being followed. The sun was a welcome ally, many of the dangerous beings that lurked in those particular lands were only hunters of the night, but the danger was still there. I pressed on, and seeing a dark forest up ahead motivated my legs to continue to run. It would be near impossible for any pursuers to find me in the thick forest, but I knew not what awaited me deep in the dark growth of mangled trees.”<br>
              <br>
“I entered into the forest, the sunshine disappeared completely as the darkness engulfed me. My eyes, for I had two then, were normally accustomed to the lack of light. Strangely though, I could not see anything in this forest. Feeling my way through at a steady clip, I began to grow weary. I had expected the forest to be smaller than what it actually was, and when I realized that no end to it was in sight, I collapsed to the ground.” <br>
              <br>
“With my hands extended out before me though, I could feel a flat stone surface. Desiring to know what lie before me, I crawled toward the stone surface. The stone structure felt like a wall or possibly the face of a cliff and was oddly cold in the warm temperature of the forest. I felt my way across the structure and came to a wooden door, which proved to me that it actually was a wall, unless someone had installed a door into a cliff side. I found nothing to open the door with though, and shoving on the door also had no effect. The door would not budge one inch. I fell to the ground again, utterly exhausted from running for my life all day.” <br>
              <br>
“As I lay on the ground I heard a strange whooshing sound. I struggled to determine what the noise could have possibly been, for it did not sound familiar to any forest noises I had heard in my lifetime. I reached my hand out again and felt for the door, but it wasn’t there. I became very scared at that moment, but I knew what awaited me if I was found by my master. I got up and stumbled through the opening. A nasty odor met me when I entered. Feeling the inside of the stone wall, I made my way around the interior of the structure. From what I could tell, it was a square room with only one entrance and had no windows of any type. Still tired from running all night, I slumped down against the wall and slept the whole night through.”<br>
              <br>
“I awoke to the sound of something scraping against the stone floor. The sound made my skin crawl, it sounded like nothing I had ever heard before. I kept still, but noticed that it seemed to be making its way toward me. Then it stopped. I could only hear the sound of the ominous breeze blowing through the forest outside. Then it said something.” <br>
              <br>
“ ‘Who has dared enter my home?’ Its voice was the most ghastly thing I had ever heard, trailing off into the darkness and piercing the soul of whoever heard its deathly whispering. My whole body froze to the spot.”<br>
              <br>
“ ‘Who has dared enter my home?’, it asked me again in the same unfeeling tone of voice. I did not answer and I did not move, I only wished I had not entered into the building. The scraping had now started again and began to move closer. I only listened, hoping it did not know where I was or that it would go away. The noise was now very close, taunting me to run, but I could not. Again the scraping stopped, I guessed that whatever it was, it was now right in front of me.” <br>
              <br>
“Suddenly I felt something slash across my face. It hurt more than anything I had ever felt before, even more than the tortures and whippings of my old master. I could feel that my eye had been lost from the attack, but there was no difference in what I saw, because I could not see anything anyway. I winced away the pain and drew my sword, slashing it down in front of me. I hit nothing but the stone floor. Then I heard the thing laugh, a distorted laugh that only something of a purely evil nature could make. Once again I slashed down, hitting nothing but the floor. The laugh rang out again. I was terrified, but drew strength from the mocking of whatever haunted this stone hut in the middle of the forest. Making one last attempt to kill the thing, I got up and dashed across the floor in front of me while swinging my weapon wildly, hoping that I might connect with whatever it was that had attacked me. The laughing stopped abruptly. Then it cried out at me.”<br>
              <br>
“ ‘Come no further! Stop! I command you! No! You can’t do this to m-!’ The cry stopped abruptly when I crashed through a glass object standing in the middle of the room. The glass pierced into my skin as I fell onto the floor. Having dropped my sword when I crashed into the object, I immediately began searching the floor for it, all the while ignoring the glass splinters getting into my hands and knees as I searched. Then I felt something else on the floor. A rolled up scroll. I could not read it though, for it was too dark, so I stuffed it into my pocket and continued searching for my weapon. Then I found something else. A bead necklace. Not being concerned with petty jewelry at the time, I strapped it around my neck and continued searching.”<br>
              <br>
“As I searched and continued to find nothing I began to wonder about the things I had found. Why had the creature stopped talking when I ran into the glass object? Why had there been a scroll and a bead necklace lying on the ground? Were they inside the glass object I had broken? Where was the creature? Why hadn’t I found or heard any signs of it yet? These questions bounced around in my head as I searched for my weapon. The time passed by and I found nothing else, except for the remains of the glass splinters that had not embedded themselves into my hands yet. Having gone over the whole floor countless times, I finally gave up my search and headed back to the doorway, but there was no door. I figured that I had probably miscalculated the direction to the doorway. I turned the other way and walked toward the opposing wall, but when I met that wall, there was no door there either. I became frustrated for a few moments, wondering where the door might be. Suddenly, I had a stroke of genius and came up with a better approach, feeling my way along the inside of the structure.” <br>
              <br>
“No door was to be found. From what I could tell, it had vanished and been replaced by more wall. I was trapped. I tried in vain to somehow knock the wall down. Accomplishing nothing but to bruise myself. I fell to the ground, feeling defeated. Yet, I felt a tingling on my body where I had placed the scroll in my pocket. Curious as to what this artifact was, I hauled it back out of my pocket. Opening up the scroll, I jumped backward suddenly as the letters in the scroll lit up brightly, tracing beams of scorching, bright light into the dark room. I held the scroll out in front of me, looking away from the burning letters. The letters soon began to die down, until they finally glowed just enough to be read. Intrigued by the scroll, I held it up and stared at the words. They were written in a language unknown to me. For some reason though, I was able to fully understand what it said. I slowly read the scroll out loud in the room, each word disappearing from the scroll as I read it:<br>
<br>
                           <br>
                            ‘In my grasp lies powers untold, <br>
                            A healing touch and gifts made of gold, <br>
                            Creating a giant and masking the old, <br>
                            Imparting my vigor to those who behold.  <br>
                            My life has begun, my secrets unfold. <br>
                            Fighting the evils of darkness, and cold,<br>
                            Rewarding the lives of those who are bold.<br>
                            Destroying all those whose hearts are of mold.<br>
                            Straight into evil my brother’s been pulled,<br>
                            I hope that one day I may break evil’s hold. <br>
                            For you have discovered the great Quolijold.’ ”<br>
 <br>
              <br>
“As I uttered that last word the whole scroll flashed brightly in my hand and then turned back to normal. I threw it down, not knowing why though, almost as if something in the back of my mind had told me to. The scroll burst into blue colored flames as it hit the stone floor. Sparks flew in every direction then slowly drifted back to the floor, fading into nothing. Next, I felt the bead necklace around my neck. Another tingling sensation same as the scroll. I reached around and pulled it off, cautiously eyeing the thing. As I held it, it began to emanate a dull light, illuminating the small room so that I could see around it. Everything that I had previously perceived the room to be, turned out to be a total lie.”<br>
              <br>
“The whole room was imbued with magic. The walls and floor of the room were not made of stone, as I had originally thought, but were composed entirely of a substance that glittered like diamonds. I felt the wall, again it felt like rough stone. Even my footsteps made the sound that only the slapping of bare feet against stone could make. The ceiling was entirely nonexistent, the limbs of trees were entwined closely together over the building, which gave protection from the elements just as good, or better, than any ceiling could provide. The door was visible now too, appearing as a shimmering, reddish colored portal of some kind that was set into the wall. I looked to the center of the floor, gasping at the thing that was there.” <br>
              <br>
“The top half of a person’s body lay unmoving on its stomach, wearing the upper part of a suit of plate mail and holding a vicious looking scimitar in one hand. Why I had not found it earlier was beyond me. I crept closer to the body and peered at the finely crafted armor. It was of an exotic design, with curved spikes coming out in places. The armor had many layers, each one overlapping the other and being spaced out slightly to allow for venting, but not spaced out enough to let a weapon through. Wishing to identify the felled warrior, I flipped the body onto its back.”<br>
              <br>
“In the helm was the face of a skeleton, its jaw dislocated in a grisly way. I jumped back at the sight, but remembered that it was dead and returned to examining it. Being the greedy little goblin I was, I attempted to lift the helm off its head and claim it for my own. The head came with it though. Being overly hasty and once again showing my utterly low intelligence, I became overcome with greed and put the illuminating beads into my pocket instead of back around my neck. I figured that sacrificing the light so that I could remove the skeleton’s head would be a small price to pay.” <br>
              <br>
“I dropped the helm to the ground though when I felt something like a hand of steel grip my arm. I could not see what it was though, for I had put the beads into my pocket. I attempted to bring the beads back out with my free hand, but I was stopped when my arm was suddenly slashed violently. The pain was almost like when I had been slashed in the face earlier. I quickly thrust my hand toward my pocket again and this time successfully retrieved the beads. As I pulled them out, the grip loosened slightly. Looking down, I saw that the headless, legless skeleton had brought itself into an upright position and now held my wrist. Its other arm hung limp at its side, still holding the scimitar. I stared in complete horror at the thing as it slipped off my arm and toppled back to the floor.” <br>
              <br>
“The beads had stopped it… twice now. Each time they had been exposed to the room, the skeleton had ceased from doing anything. I knew at that moment that there was something very special about the beads and desired to find out more about them.”<br>
              <br>
“As I put the beads around my neck again, something different from before happened. The room suddenly became very small, the tree limbs nearly touching my head as the room shrunk before my eyes. I decided to pass through the portal on the other side of the room so that I could escape, in case I was crushed. When I started to move though, it seemed like I was walking on stilts. My balance was not as good as it had been before, but I felt revived and strengthened. As I walked outside, I noticed that I was once again seriously mistaken about many things.”<br>
              <br>
“The beads still glowed with light, allowing me to see some of the area around me. Everything appeared three times as small as it used to be. Tree limbs that previously loomed over my head were now nearly eye level. The trees themselves were not as large as I had remembered either, not being any wider than meself. I suddenly noticed how far away the ground appeared to be and became frightened. I cautiously lowered meself to a crawling position. The truth of the moment suddenly came upon me then as I looked down at my arms. To put it truthfully, from what had previously been there, these were practically two tree trunks. I glanced down at the rest of my body and saw that it still showed the whip marks from my old master, but everything else had changed. In place of my hanging belly was a washboard stomach. Instead of mere toothpicks, my legs were now gigantic and muscled. My whole body had changed from a twisted and gnarled frame into a warrior’s dream.”<br>
              <br>
“I also felt as if a load had been taken off my brain. Everything that I had not understood before was beginning to make sense now. Only I still had no idea what had just occurred and why my thoughts were so much easier to conjure up now. These things were meaningless to me though, I still retained my old hatred for my master.”  <br>
              <br>
“That day I took it upon meself to find Grimbulkin and show him what it meant to be tortured. I never did find him, but I learned much from the experience, as I also have learned much about the powers of this necklace. The powers that it bestows upon its wearer are many times beyond my comprehension though, for there is also much that I do not understand about it as of yet, especially what occurred in the magical room that I retrieved the beads from. I may never learn what truly happened there, but I believe with all my heart that I would not have lived if I had not found the magical beads.”<br>
              <br>
Kilmituk stopped then and wiped some sweat from his forehead. Then he took a flask of water from his side and took a long gulp of its contents. Putting it back he returned his gaze to Dharshan. <br>
              <br>
“So is the story of my life, but I must get some rest now,” with that Kilmituk leaned back on the edge of the large crater that had formed around his body in the soft ground and closed his eye. Dharshan was still trying to figure out the mysteries of Kilmituk’s story and was caught off guard when the goblin suddenly decided he wanted to go to sleep again.<br>
